 *1276181321* Drucker's Leverage Memo for Post-Capitalist Society: what is an organization?
 Today's <a href="http://www.amazon.co.jp/gp/product/447800210X?ie=UTF8&tag=nishiohirokaz-22&linkCode=as2&camp=247&creative=7399& creativeASIN=447800210X">Leverage notes from Chapter 2, "The Coming of the Organizational Society," in Drucker's Famous Books 8: Post-Capitalist Society</a>.
 
 >>
 We are too specialized today. The academy is particularly bad. But the solution is not to teach liberal arts courses. That will not work. Experts only achieve results when they are experts. P.67
 <<
 
 >>
 An organization is a purpose-oriented institution. Organizations are tools. Like any other tool, an organization enhances its ability to carry out its purpose by specializing. P.71-72
 <<
 
 >>
 All 250 members of the orchestra are experts. All members of the orchestra play with the same sheet music. P.73
 <<
 An orchestra is a group of professionals with separate expertise, focused on a single purpose. An oboe player does not play the violin.
 
 >>
 Societies, communities, and families are sustaining institutions. They seek stability and seek to prevent change. In contrast, organizations in post-capitalist societies are institutions of change.
 
 The function of an organization is to apply knowledge to tools, processes, and products, to work, and to knowledge itself. Thus, organizations are constantly changing and innovating. Innovation is, as Schumpeter said, creative destruction.
 <<
 Incidentally, <a href='http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%83%A8%E3%83%BC%E3%82%BC%E3%83%95 %E3%83%BB%E3%82%B7%E3%83%A5%E3%83%B3%E3%83%9A%E3%83 BC%E3%82%BF%E3%83 %BC'>Joseph Schumpeter</a> is
 >>
 When an entrepreneur implements an innovation, the economy is disturbed, but the growing imbalance is the process of a boom. On the other hand, a recession was considered to be a process in which the economy as a whole responds to the new situation brought about by innovation by following the lead firms that have obtained monopoly profits, and the economy gradually returns to equilibrium due to credit contraction (repayment to banks).
 <<
 In other words, he says, "When an economy stabilizes without change, it is a recession. He said, "Humans are either progressing or regressing, there is no in-between. To think that the status quo is being maintained is actually evidence of regression." (Shinzo Mori) is one of my favorite quotes.
 
 >>
 Marx said that the greatest change that capitalism brought to society was the alienation of the working people. Workers did not have the means of production. They could only produce when they were loaned increasingly expensive opportunities by capitalists. P.86
 
 The relationship between employees as knowledge workers and the means of production is interdependent. Neither can function without the other. P.87
 <<
 Of course, knowledge workers here are not just "non-physical workers," but workers who have expertise that is irreplaceable.
 
 >>
 Historically, workers have been supervised. Knowledge workers, on the other hand, cannot be supervised. It is useless to have someone who knows more about your specialty than you do. P.87
 <<
 
 This is 34 of 277 pages, less than 20% of the total. That's about the price of two bottles of juice.
